Etymology. This species was named by combining two Rapanui words, manu and kio . Manu is a general term for “insect” or “bug,” while kio is the verb “to hide”, thus “hiding bug.” During times of war and conflict on the island, the Rapanui people would seek refuge in caves (
Routledge 2007
). These caves are known as ana kionga or "caves for hiding."

